<typeStatus id="54F888563642FF8D2A7AF9E5FD969660" box="[531,575,1587,1608]" pageId="37" pageNumber="244">type</typeStatus>
locality is situated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C359657F3641FF8E28DBFF0CFE93938C" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BFC36F43641FF8E28DBFF0CFCDD9148" blockId="38.[178,1085,218,352]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">
Description: Body length 
<quantity id="4CBB9B113641FF8E2A73FF0CFDC390C7" box="[538,618,218,240]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" unit="mm" value="4.6">4.6 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 2.0 mm. Coloration: head blackish-brown; pronotum dark-brown; elytra brown, with the postero-lateral angles diffusely darker; abdomen brown, with segments VIII-X and the posterior margins of segments III-VII reddish, and with the anterior portions of segments VI-VII blackish; legs yellowish; antennae dark-brown, with antennomeres I-II reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFC36F43641FF8E28DBFEB8FD6A9227" blockId="38.[178,1085,366,528]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">
Head (
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E2893FEB8FEFC91AC" box="[250,341,366,388]" captionStart="Figs 137-144" captionStartId="37.[178,218,1308,1330]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,212,1284]" captionTargetId="figure-1@37.[179,1083,212,1299]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Figs 137-144: Nepalota daweiana nov.sp. (137-143) and N. martensi PACE from Yunnan (144): (137) forebody; (138) antenna; (139) male tergite VIII; (140) male sternite VIII; (141, 144) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (142) apical portion of median lobe of aedeagus in ventral view; (143) paramere. Scale bars: 137: 0.5 mm; 138-144: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414224/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Fig. 137</figureCitation>
) transverse, approximately 1.1 times as broad as long, widest behind eyes; dorsal surface with distinct microreticulation; punctation sparse and extremely fine, barely noticeable. Eyes moderately large and weakly convex, approximately as long as postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna (
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E2A07FE14FD6F91F0" box="[622,710,450,472]" captionStart="Figs 137-144" captionStartId="37.[178,218,1308,1330]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,212,1284]" captionTargetId="figure-1@37.[179,1083,212,1299]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Figs 137-144: Nepalota daweiana nov.sp. (137-143) and N. martensi PACE from Yunnan (144): (137) forebody; (138) antenna; (139) male tergite VIII; (140) male sternite VIII; (141, 144) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (142) apical portion of median lobe of aedeagus in ventral view; (143) paramere. Scale bars: 137: 0.5 mm; 138-144: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414224/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Fig. 138</figureCitation>
) slender, 
<quantity id="4CBB9B113641FF8E2B42FE14FCD091FF" box="[811,889,450,472]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.6 mm</quantity>
long; antennomere distinctly IV oblong; preapical antennomeres as long as broad; antennomere XI apically acute, longer than the combined length of IX and X.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFC36F43641FF8E28DBFDC8FDE89244" blockId="38.[178,1085,542,620]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E294DFDC8FED2921C" box="[292,379,542,564]" captionStart="Figs 137-144" captionStartId="37.[178,218,1308,1330]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,212,1284]" captionTargetId="figure-1@37.[179,1083,212,1299]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Figs 137-144: Nepalota daweiana nov.sp. (137-143) and N. martensi PACE from Yunnan (144): (137) forebody; (138) antenna; (139) male tergite VIII; (140) male sternite VIII; (141, 144) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (142) apical portion of median lobe of aedeagus in ventral view; (143) paramere. Scale bars: 137: 0.5 mm; 138-144: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414224/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Fig. 137</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.2 times as broad as long and 1.35 times as broad as head; disc with distinct microreticulation; punctation rather dense and very fine, but slightly more distinct than that of head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFC36F43641FF8E28DBFDACFCCA9284" blockId="38.[178,1085,634,684]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E2896FDACFEFE92B8" box="[255,343,634,656]" captionStart="Figs 137-144" captionStartId="37.[178,218,1308,1330]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,212,1284]" captionTargetId="figure-1@37.[179,1083,212,1299]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Figs 137-144: Nepalota daweiana nov.sp. (137-143) and N. martensi PACE from Yunnan (144): (137) forebody; (138) antenna; (139) male tergite VIII; (140) male sternite VIII; (141, 144) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (142) apical portion of median lobe of aedeagus in ventral view; (143) paramere. Scale bars: 137: 0.5 mm; 138-144: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414224/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Fig. 137</figureCitation>
) 0.95 times as long as pronotum; punctation very dense and moderately fine; interstices with microreticulation. Hind wings fully developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFC36F43641FF8E28DBFD6CFBBB92C4" blockId="38.[178,1085,698,748]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Abdomen with very shallow transverse microsculpture; punctation moderately dense on tergites III-VI, sparser on tergite VII; tergites III and VII without sexual dimorphism.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFC36F43641FF8E28DBFD2CFBBD93A8" blockId="38.[178,1085,762,896]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">
♂: tergite VIII (
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E290FFD2CFE6A9338" box="[358,451,762,784]" captionStart="Figs 137-144" captionStartId="37.[178,218,1308,1330]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,212,1284]" captionTargetId="figure-1@37.[179,1083,212,1299]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Figs 137-144: Nepalota daweiana nov.sp. (137-143) and N. martensi PACE from Yunnan (144): (137) forebody; (138) antenna; (139) male tergite VIII; (140) male sternite VIII; (141, 144) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (142) apical portion of median lobe of aedeagus in ventral view; (143) paramere. Scale bars: 137: 0.5 mm; 138-144: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414224/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Fig. 139</figureCitation>
) with posterior margin obtusely angled in the middle, not crenulate; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E29C1FCC0FE579304" box="[424,510,790,812]" captionStart="Figs 137-144" captionStartId="37.[178,218,1308,1330]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,212,1284]" captionTargetId="figure-1@37.[179,1083,212,1299]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Figs 137-144: Nepalota daweiana nov.sp. (137-143) and N. martensi PACE from Yunnan (144): (137) forebody; (138) antenna; (139) male tergite VIII; (140) male sternite VIII; (141, 144) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (142) apical portion of median lobe of aedeagus in ventral view; (143) paramere. Scale bars: 137: 0.5 mm; 138-144: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414224/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Fig. 140</figureCitation>
) oblong, distinctly longer than tergite VIII, and strongly convex posteriorly; median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E2AEFFCE4FCA69360" box="[646,783,818,840]" captionStart="Figs 137-144" captionStartId="37.[178,218,1308,1330]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,212,1284]" captionTargetId="figure-1@37.[179,1083,212,1299]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Figs 137-144: Nepalota daweiana nov.sp. (137-143) and N. martensi PACE from Yunnan (144): (137) forebody; (138) antenna; (139) male tergite VIII; (140) male sternite VIII; (141, 144) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (142) apical portion of median lobe of aedeagus in ventral view; (143) paramere. Scale bars: 137: 0.5 mm; 138-144: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414224/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Figs 141-142</figureCitation>
) approximately 
<quantity id="4CBB9B113641FF8E2BDCFCE4FBAA936F" box="[949,1027,818,839]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
long; ventral process and internal structures of distinctive shapes; crista apicalis pronounced; paramere (
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E2977FCBCFEDD93A8" box="[286,372,874,896]" captionStart="Figs 137-144" captionStartId="37.[178,218,1308,1330]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,212,1284]" captionTargetId="figure-1@37.[179,1083,212,1299]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Figs 137-144: Nepalota daweiana nov.sp. (137-143) and N. martensi PACE from Yunnan (144): (137) forebody; (138) antenna; (139) male tergite VIII; (140) male sternite VIII; (141, 144) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (142) apical portion of median lobe of aedeagus in ventral view; (143) paramere. Scale bars: 137: 0.5 mm; 138-144: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414224/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Fig. 143</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as median lobe and with short apical lobe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFC36F43641FF8E28DBFC42FE93938C" blockId="38.[178,314,910,937]" box="[178,314,910,937]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">
<specimenCount id="9D45FD7D3641FF8E28DBFC42FF6E9381" box="[178,199,916,937]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C359657F3641FF8E28DBFC6DFE3A944A" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BFC36F43641FF8E28DBFC6DFE3A944A" blockId="38.[178,1085,955,1123]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">
Comparative notes: This species is distinguished from its congeners particularly by the shapes of the median lobe of the aedeagus and of the male tergite and sternite VIII, from the similar 
<taxonomicName id="4C434D773641FF8E2999FC20FDC19423" box="[496,616,1014,1035]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nepalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="martensi">
<emphasis id="B937EAE63641FF8E2999FC20FDC19423" box="[496,616,1014,1035]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">N. martensi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
additionally by the unmodified male tergites III and VII and the smaller and less convex eyes (
<taxonomicName id="4C434D773641FF8E2AC4FBC5FC8A9400" box="[685,803,1043,1064]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nepalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="martensi">
<emphasis id="B937EAE63641FF8E2AC4FBC5FC8A9400" box="[685,803,1043,1064]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">N. martensi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: eyes distinctly longer than postocular region in dorsal view). For comparison, the aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C434D773641FF8E2BCBFBE7FBB6946E" box="[930,1055,1073,1094]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nepalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="martensi">
<emphasis id="B937EAE63641FF8E2BCBFBE7FBB6946E" box="[930,1055,1073,1094]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">N. martensi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is illustrated in 
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E2951FB9BFE3A944A" box="[312,403,1101,1123]" captionStart="Figs 137-144" captionStartId="37.[178,218,1308,1330]" captionTargetBox="[189,1083,212,1284]" captionTargetId="figure-1@37.[179,1083,212,1299]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Figs 137-144: Nepalota daweiana nov.sp. (137-143) and N. martensi PACE from Yunnan (144): (137) forebody; (138) antenna; (139) male tergite VIII; (140) male sternite VIII; (141, 144) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view; (142) apical portion of median lobe of aedeagus in ventral view; (143) paramere. Scale bars: 137: 0.5 mm; 138-144: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414224" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414224/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Fig. 144.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C359657F3641FF8E28DBFBADFE20952D" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BFC36F43641FF8E28DBFBADFE20952D" blockId="38.[178,1086,1147,1286]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">
Distribution and natural history: The type locality is situated in the Dawei 
<collectingRegion id="4987F8163641FF8E2948FB4EFEFD9486" box="[289,340,1176,1198]" country="Myanmar" name="Shan" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Shan</collectingRegion>
Virgin Forest Park, to the southeast of Pingbian, southern 
<collectingRegion id="4987F8163641FF8E2BC6FB4EFC569485" box="[943,1023,1176,1197]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E2C64FB4EFF1794E3" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="3.[178,223,811,832]" captionTargetBox="[178,1082,212,801]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1082,212,801]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Map 1: Distributions of Nepalota chinensis PACE (filled circles) and N. martensi PACE (open circles), based on examined and reliable literature records." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414159/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">Map 1</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="54F888563641FF8E296BFB63FEF294E3" box="[258,347,1205,1227]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">holotype</typeStatus>
was sifted from leaf litter at an altitude of 
<quantity id="4CBB9B113641FF8E2B66FB63FCF794E3" box="[783,862,1205,1227]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" unit="m" value="2100.0">2100 m</quantity>
, together with several other undescribed species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C434D773641FF8E29B0FB04FDC194C0" box="[473,616,1234,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Staphylinidae</taxonomicName>
. For a photograph of the type locality see 
<figureCitation id="13782A713641FF8E2C7CFB04FF62952D" captionStart="Figs 9-15" captionStartId="9.[178,218,1138,1160]" captionTargetBox="[186,1082,225,1117]" captionTargetId="figure-1@9.[178,1082,212,1129]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 9-15: Nepalota franzi PACE from Gansu: (9) male tergite VIII; (10) male sternite VIII; (11) paramere; (12) ventral process of aedeagus in ventral view; (13) female tergite VIII; (14) female sternite VIII; (15) spermatheca. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5414169" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5414169/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="245">
Fig. 
<quantity id="4CBB9B113641FF8E28DBFB26FF62952D" box="[178,203,1264,1285]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" unit="in" value="12.0">12</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD24B053641FF8E2885FB26FE2C952D" author="ASSING V" box="[236,389,1263,1285]" pageId="38" pageNumber="245" pagination="63 - 71" refId="ref22104" refString="ASSING V. (2015): A revision of Amarochara THOMSON of the Holarctic region V. A new species from China, a new combination, the male of A. caeca ASSING, and additional records (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae: Aleocharini). - Linzer Biologische Beitrage 47 (1): 63 - 71." type="journal article" year="2015">ASSING (2015)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
